Well worth the trip
Sep 2024 • Couples
The guided English tour was excellent. There were just two of us so we essentially had a private tour. Our guide provided so much detail as to the history of the site and he answered all our questions very well. This house is not as well known as other Gaudi sites so it was very quiet when we first arrived in the morning. It got a little busier by the time we left but not crowded. This was a really interesting site (one of my favorites). We took a taxi to the house since we were running late but walked to the metro and took the metro back afterwards. Not a long walk at all. Highly recommend.

Don't miss this hidden gem
Sep 2024 • Family
This little gem is such good value for money! We went here the day after we had been to Sagrada Familia and the contrast couldn't have been more stark, this was a much more enjoyable experience. The house was peaceful, no heaving crowds, we could see and enjoy everything that was described in the audio guide, without having to jostle for space or move out of the way of others. The friendly staff spoke good English and did not hurry us, even when it was close to closing time. The young guide in the house really helped us to appreciate more than the audio guide alone. The only thing to note is that the official website for tickets didn't come up as the top hit on our browser search and I had to dig a bit more to get tickets. Presumably that will change as it becomes a more popular tourist site.

A tourist destintion without many tourists.
Sep 2024 • Family
The house was unique. The outside showed Gaudi's influence but without the heavy use of coloured tiles to cover the walls. It was a similar story inside the house. We really appreciated the quietness after the hectic pace of the city centre. There was only a few other visitors when we went to the house and the entry fee was extremely reasonable compared to the other Gaudi houses in the city. We also really appreciated the patience of the young man who escorted us around the property. There was no rush and he spoke good English. The gardens were pretty as well.

Another Gaudi Treasure
May 2023 • Couples
A fifteen minute or so walk from the funicular at Tibado is this little treat. A lot smaller than La Sagrada or Park Guell it is nevertheless a fascinating looking building.

There are organised tours here but our timing was off so an audioguide did us just fine, this was included in the not too bad entry fee of 12 euros each. We probably spent about an hour here walking the grounds and the tower itself, to enter the tower they seem to have a limit to the number of people at a time so have timed intervals with a brief introduction/tour on your entry.

As with all Gaudi's designs nature features heavily, my particular highlight was the roof, which look like lizards dragons when you are up there.

Like Tibado just up the road this is a great place to visit especially if you have seen the highlights of central Barcelona.

permia
Ireland65,657 contributions
By the Master modelled on a Medieval Castle
Feb 2023
It was a superb visit, with no booking or queuing required. Perfect time to visit, in the bright blue sky and sun filled morning.

Modelled on a medieval castle that occupied the site and commissioned by Jaume Figueres in 1900, Gaudi was advised that money would not be limited. His designs conserved the style of the castle, still beautifully seen today.

His signature early motif are visible, both inside and out. An ornate staircase leads to fascinating higher floors. A contrast between the lovely plastered walls and the unfinished brick work is great to see. The latter a consequence of Figueres dying before completion and his widow being unable to fund it to the finish.

In the brickwork it’s possible to see pencil marks made by Gaudi indicating precise placements that he wanted. Evidence of his paramount attention to the detail of his designs.

Interesting that top windows are not just windows. Ascending to the roof it’s obvious that they also represent the face of a dragon, a creature that Gaudi fell in awe of early in his career.

Bellesguard means beautiful vistas and these were certainly to be seen from the rooftop and the balcony, out upon which it is possible to step.
Written March 5, 2023
